2) The first was a practical reason to compress, the second is more creative. Compression allows us to shape the envelope of sounds, by varying the attack and release and type of compressor we use (we'll come back to that). Why would that be useful? A few examples;

- A fast attack allows us to tame the front of a sound, and set it back in an arrangement. Our ears are naturally drawn to shorter sharper transients, and that can be a lovely thing. But say for example I've got a bright and transient heavy acoustic guitar, it might be distracting me from the vocal and the story of the song, a fast attack and low ratio could allow me to "set it back" behind the vocal, without turning it down or darkening it too much

- Another way we can use the envelope shaping is to bring out the body or thump in a sound. Take something like a bright snare crack, a compressor like a DBX160 will grab the front transient and soften it, and then the release curve will give the body and shell of the snare this chunky weight that can be really musical

@bobby k i love the way it sounds on a modern record. the right amount and kind of clipping compresses the sound in a way that a compressor or limiter doesn't do. 

when i'm making music with drum samples (which is almost everything) the clipping of the music buss and/or mix buss creates the right kind of aggressive cohesion i'm looking for. when it works the best, it softens transients the right amount while glueing the excitement of programmed music together.

clipping doesn't work nearly as well for me when i have organic drums, because the transients are much more delicate in live performed drum track. i also don't clip much when it's an acoustic song or not dominated by programmed drums. clipping tends to work best for me when the dominant transients are consistent

@Jodonny  What I do as an exercise to get my head in the game when I know I'm not hearing things right, is to either have a really hot or really cold shower - I can't say for sure why this works for me, but if I was to rationalise it, I'd say it's because it shocks my mind into a heightened state of awareness, probably due to the shock of the extreme temperature change. I stick it out for around 10 minutes, and when I go back I'm almost always hearing things the way I should be.

And if I've the time, for an extra boost of awareness, when I come back from my shower I spend about 10-20 minutes just listening to music of a similar genre to what I'm working on, without changing the volume level between songs or when I go back to my DAW. When I stick to this routine I usually do my best work.

I've also *really* fucked up some mixes due to attempting to get them done when I ain't hearing things right. I also have sinus issues, but maybe my senses aren't warmed up. I dunno. The human body is crazy

@Zakhiggins there's some opinions that say keeping pro tools faders at or around zero is best because it gives the largest dynamic range for pro tools to work with when it does its summing. when doing the type of mixing that Jon, Teezio, etc do, you're dealing with stems where you're starting with everything coming up at zero anyway (you load up the stems, everything is at zero, and it sounds like the mix). so any adjustments you make to the sound in processing (compressors, saturators, eq, etc) aren't big gain changes anyway. so you just use the plugins's output control to compensate, thus keeping the faders around zero.

that's how I understand it, anyway. 

ps, i don't do this because I'm almost always mixing my own production sessions. it would be insane for me to try and completely rework everything to have faders at zero in one of my production sessions.

@bobby k I don’t mix so I won’t try to give you mix advice. But I share one thing that may help

When I broadened my conception of what mastering was from making a thing to helping clients cross a threshold from “anything’s possible” to “we’re done” good things started to happen

It might be worth thinking about your role in a bigger way. Notes are inevitable, if chasing wow or safe or whatever on V1 limits you later in the client journey it may not be worth the trade off

@h3x Everywhere! Driving it into fx  can real nice, as is the general OD, very harmonic!
I'm waiting on the Hw DSP to get it on my buses but if you're in the box I highly suspect it would kill on drum/mix bus.
 The compressor is fucking awesome as well, there's something really cool that happens between the input level and the  distortion curve of the compressor, I'm not sure how to explain it but overall the whole plugin is super versatile

@Eric Martin thanks for your reply man, re: clippers vs compression......yes i am familiar with that. I dont use compression for dynamics control either....you may have heard of the "clip to zero" strategy? i do a similar thing but then output my limiters/clippers at -6db instead of 0. Its similar to what johns doing just catching peaks and not squashing the life out of everythin....mike dean does it too IIRC. 

Re: spectral shaper : I didnt actually spot jon using his spectral shaper in that 1-6khz region, i saw it in the low mids....so having heard you and @oaklandmatt both mention it ...it seems hes defo already using this high mid scoop trick then! Ill still research the maths of the lufs algo because i like to really understand the psycho-acoustics and science of these sorts of things. Im after the ultimate mix in this life, lol .....i come from underground club music, where drums and bass and a sweet vocal are everything so its a constant balance/re-balance between lows/mids and highs as i learn more advanced techniques

..re: jons mix yesterday and clipping, and you mention clipping the attack portion of a sounds adsr , did you notice how much he uses transient shapers on almost everything? v clever. Personally, i love transients and fight hard to keep them and jons trick of putting a transient shaper after a clipper/limiter has been a revelation....(thanks @oaklandmatt , that gem came from your LWMR) .....bruce swedien said compression is for children, and i believe he evangelised about not killing transients ...i love a transient shaper and a clipper ....compressor , not so much.

@Gazing Wrmth | Mixes & Masters I’m pretty much exclusively in cans and i second all of what Noah said. Additionally, sonarworks for your headphones is definitely worth it esp. for only 70 USD. It will smear transients a bit, but you can get over that if you reference well. Mix quiet and you won’t be disappointed. 

Forgot to mention, because DT 770s are closed back, making sure you have a good seal and taking breaks are critical. You need a 15 minute break for every hour you put in on cans, bare minimum IMO. Without that, attention loss and fatigue kick in. 

Tools like tonal balance control 2 are important. I recommend setting up a Pro-MB with 3-5 bands across the entire frequency range but make them all neutral with no compression. Sub, low, mid, high mid, top end. You can monitor specific ranges now. And for sub/low end, you can turn the gain up on your headphone mix a bit, isolate the low end, and you can hear it a bit better. Make sure you turn your headphones down a bit before you un-solo the low or the sub, but this has helped me massively

@Juliette Ok having heard the track, there’s a solo synth bass in there which is well designed sonically, when that drops out and the bass guitar comes back in, everything from about 60-70 cycles and below disappears except for the kick. So yeah I’d first try pumping low end into it, be it with EQ or subharmonic, followed by some (a lot) of compression. I’m sure better people here have a better way to do this. 

The DI itself doesn’t have any overtones other than stuff you’re finding unflattering, so you could try mult’ing the DI signal out to an amp sim (even some guitar amps work here) to fill out the spectrum that the guitars aren’t fulfilling 

I’d also say the bass drum could use some augmenting of the low end  and maybe a bit of length in order to emphasise that impact. Because the synth bass atm has all the power, and isn’t omnipresent, so it’s leaving the rest of the arrangement even _more_ neutered as a result
